{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506563"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2547"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2547"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.01,0.07,0.08,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78993"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2547"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64342"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1817"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"},{"type":"tags","id":"11198"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42522"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43183"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78993"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with recent-onset muscle aches. Two months ago, he was hospitalised due to ST-elevation myocardial infarction and started on aspirin, nebivolol, simvastatin, and lisinopril. He has a medical history of hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and hypertriglyceridaemia for which he takes amlodipine, metformin, sitagliptin, and gemfibrozil. He also presented with muscle stiffness in the shoulders one month ago and was treated with low-dose corticosteroid. On examination, there is tenderness in his thigh muscles and slightly reduced muscle strength. Laboratory results are shown below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin = 135 g/L (130-170 g/L)\u003Cbr /\u003EWBC = 9.8 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (3.5-11.0 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatine kinase (CK) = 324 U/L (45-250 U/L)\u003Cbr /\u003ETSH = 3.7 U/L (0.27-4.20 mIU/L)\u003Cbr /\u003EESR = 7 mm/hr (0-14 mm/hr)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glucocorticoid-induced myopathy","Dermatomyositis","Polymyalgia rheumatica","Polymyositis","Statin-induced myopathy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u2019s muscle pain and weakness could be due to a number of different causes. His elevated CK, normal ESR, and normal TSH, along with a recent history of simvastatin use, are suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Estatin-induced myopathy\u003C/strong\u003E (SIM). The use of statins increases the risk of SIM, especially when used together with a fibrate. This patient is on gemfibrozil, and subsequent use of a statin drug significantly increases his risk of developing SIM. SIM is characterised by muscle pain, elevated CK, normal ESR, and normal TSH. In severe cases, SIM can lead to rhabdomyolysis, which is associated with myoglobinuria and acute kidney injury. Patients with mild muscle pain should be transferred to another statin or have their original statin dose lowered. Patients who present with rhabdomyolysis should have their statins discontinued immediately and appropriately managed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucocorticoid-induced myopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility given the recent corticosteroid use, but it typically presents with muscle weakness without significant pain and normal CK levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatomyositis\u003C/strong\u003E would present with skin changes and a more significant elevation in CK, which are not observed here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyalgia rheumatica\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by muscle stiffness and pain, particularly in the shoulders and hips, but it usually presents with a normal CK and elevated ESR, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyositis\u003C/strong\u003E would present with muscle weakness and elevated CK, but it is often associated with systemic symptoms and elevated inflammatory markers, which are not present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Muscle pain is a well-recognised side effect of statin use.","The combination of statins and fibrates increases the risk of statin-induced myopathy."],"references":["Mo\u00dfhammer D, Schaeffeler E, Schwab M, M\u00f6rike K. Mechanisms and assessment of statin-related muscular adverse effects. Br J Clin Pharmacol. 2014 Sep;78(3):454-66. doi: 10.1111/bcp.12360. PMID: 25069381; PMCID: PMC4243897. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25069381/","Tomaszewski M, St\u0119pie\u0144 KM, Tomaszewska J, Czuczwar SJ. Statin-induced myopathies. Pharmacol Rep. 2011;63(4):859-66. doi: 10.1016/s1734-1140(11)70601-6. PMID: 22001973. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22001973/","Vinci P, Panizon E, Tosoni LM, Cerrato C, Pellicori F, Mearelli F, Biasinutto C, Fiotti N, Di Girolamo FG, Biolo G. Statin-Associated Myopathy: Emphasis on Mechanisms and Targeted Therapy. Int J Mol Sci. 2021 Oct 28;22(21):11687. doi: 10.3390/ijms222111687. PMID: 34769118; PMCID: PMC8583847. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34769118/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64342"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2547"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19915"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19915"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3089d4dc-6cba-4ed5-919a-3b48e52fe6ee.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3089d4dc-6cba-4ed5-919a-3b48e52fe6ee.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":520,"height":188}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64342"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T13:00:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T13:02:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2547"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78993"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group